<div id="description">
  <div class="container-fluid">
    <div class="col-sm-6">
      <h1>&ldquo;Learn to code&rdquo; shouldn't be one-size-fits-all</h1>
      <p>Everyone wants something different out of &ldquo;coding&rdquo; &mdash; maybe you want to <strong>make robots</strong>, or build a <strong>blog</strong>, or catalog <strong>Walt Whitman poems</strong>.</p>
      <p>Every one of those needs a different set of skills, and there's a good chance walking through a <strong>generic JavaScript tutorial</strong> won't get you there! (and it very well may bore you to death)</p>
      <p>So who better to ask what to learn than <em>everyone?</em></p>
    </div>
    <div class="col-sm-6">
      <h1>Soooo, what should a newbie learn?</h1>
      <p><strong>It depends!</strong> Tumblr customizers might look for <a href="http://www.codecademy.com/tracks/web">HTML and CSS</a>, aspiring roboticists could check out <a href="http://arduino.cc">Arduino</a>, mapping aficionados might like <a href="https://www.mapbox.com/tilemill/">TileMill</a>. The list goes on and on!</p>
      <p>We're asking people from all walks of life to <a href="/responses">explain how they code</a> and <a href="/responses">share the tools they use</a>, so maybe you can get a leg up on the Right Stuff.</p>
      <p>Oh, and I don't want kernel hackers and musicians to get into fistfights, so just pretend "code" is in quotes all over the place.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

